      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my psych dissertation and i'm stuck on a weird result. my analysis shows a p-value of 0.06 for my main effect. some people are saying it looks like a trend, but my advisor is saying it's not statistically significant. can you explain the technical reason why 0.06 fails the standard threshold? also i'm struggling to differentiate between actual signal and just random noise in this context.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, by the standard threshold of $\\alpha = 0.05$, is technically not statistically significant. This is because the p-value represents the probability of observing your data (or more extreme data) if the null hypothesis were actually true. Since 0.06 is greater than 0.05, you fail to reject the null hypothesis.\n\nThe technical reason is simple: you are saying there is a 6% chance you'd see this result just by random chance, assuming nothing interesting is going on. To claim significance, you usually want that chance to be very low, like 5% or less.\n\nWhen people talk about a \"trend,\" they are looking at the data visually, seeing a slight upward or downward slope, which is what your advisor is pointing out. It's the difference between a solid, undeniable, highly-defined signal and a faint, slightly wobbly line that might just be the residue of random noise.\n\nTo differentiate signal from noise, you need to look beyond just the p-value. Consider effect size—how *big* is that difference? A tiny difference might be statistically non-significant but still interesting, but a",
      "source": "target",
