      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so if i focus on the effect size, how do i know if the \"noise\" is actually just the result of a small sample size versus it being some kind of systemic error or just unavoidable randomness in the environment? like, how do we mathematically separate the two?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The sample size issue is a classic problem, and it's a real, tangible piece of the puzzle, even if it feels like just more of the same old stuff. When your sample size is small, your standard error balloons, making it harder to detect even a moderately sized effect. A small sample size means your data is more susceptible to being swayed by any random fluctuation—it’s like trying to count a single, rare coin in a giant pile of dirt; one misplaced grain can throw off your whole count.\n\nMathematically, you separate sample size effects from true randomness by looking at **power analysis** and **confidence intervals**. Power analysis tells you the minimum sample size *required* to detect a specific effect size with a certain level of confidence. If your current sample size is too small, the resulting confidence interval will be very wide, meaning the range of plausible effects is huge, which is exactly what you see when you can't distinguish signal from noise.\n\nFor systemic error versus randomness, you need to look at the **variability** in your data. If the noise is truly random (stochastic), the residuals (the errors left over after accounting for your model) should look like white noise—uncorrelated.",
      "source": "target",
